# Go Backend Test Placement

## Rule: All tests go in `backend-api/tests/`

NEVER place `_test.go` files in production packages (`deck/`, `auth/`, `common/`, `media/`).
Tests always go in the `tests/` directory:

```
backend-api/tests/
├── unit/            # Pure logic tests, no Redis or HTTP
│   ├── stats_test.go
│   └── spread_test.go
└── integration/     # Full HTTP handler tests with Redis
    ├── helpers_test.go
    ├── deck_test.go
    ├── fact_test.go
    └── card_test.go
```

## When to use unit vs integration

| Type | Package | Uses Redis? | Uses HTTP? | Example |
|------|---------|-------------|------------|---------|
| Unit | `package unit` | No | No | `deck.SpreadCards()`, `deck.ComputeStats()` |
| Integration | `package integration` | Yes (DB 1) | Yes (`httptest`) | `deck.AddFact` handler, `deck.CreateDeck` handler |

## Exporting for testability

If a function needs unit testing from `tests/unit/`, it must be exported (uppercase).
Unexported helpers that only need integration-level testing can stay lowercase.

```go
// Needs unit test → export it
func SpreadCards(existing []Card, new []Card) []Card { ... }

// Only tested via handler integration tests → keep unexported
func someInternalHelper() { ... }
```

## Integration test pattern

- Use `setupTestRedis(t)` and `createTestUser(t, ...)` from `helpers_test.go`
- Build a `mux.Router` with `auth.JwtAuthMiddleware` per test
- Use `httptest.NewRequest` / `httptest.NewRecorder`
- Prefer table-driven tests with `checkResponse` and `checkRedis` callbacks

## Running tests

```bash
go test ./tests/unit/...         # Unit tests (no Redis needed)
go test ./tests/integration/...  # Integration tests (requires Redis on :6379)
```
